110 Thirty-seventh Ave., north side, east of Main Street, showing the Barto Homestead in which, in 1934, a Barto still resided.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Main Street; west side, between Thirty-seventh Ave. (left) and Northern Boulevard (right), showing an old 3½-story frame hip-roofed house said to have been built, according to the City Club Guide, at the end of the 18th Century. This building in 1923 was renovated, its front changed to brick and the hip taken out of the roof, substituting a flat roof therefor. It was then known as the Riesenburger Building and was No. 27 Main Street. It was demolished in 1933. This is a set of two views.

1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Main St., west side, north of 37th Ave., showing an old home at the rears of 35 and 72 Main St. and Thirty-seventh Ave. respectively. It was moved back when Folletts store, a brick structure was erected on its site.

1922

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Main Street, east side, north of Thirty-seventh Ave., showing in the foreground (No. 30), a 2-story brick building bearing the sign "Join Our Hoosier Club." It was upon this site that the First M.E. Church was erected. This building was subsequently moved to Fortieth Ave., between Main and Union Streets, on the west side of the Armory on the north side of the street.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

1922.
